        * initial connection to server (print client IP, filename and number of chunks 
        * port numbers received by client to be connect for k chunks 
        * port numbers to which socket is bound to for the k sockets used to connect to server 
        * connection establishment message (with client IP and server port number) at server
        * completion message after transmission of each chunk at server
        * completion message after reception of each chunk at chunk
        * file downloaded and put-together message at client
        * print the time required since first file request to server to download complete. also, print avergae download rate in bytes/sec.
some JAVA classes that you might end up using:
File, RandomAccessFile, Thread, Socket, ServerSocket, DtagramSocket, BufferedReader, InputStreamReader, 
OutputStreamReader, PrintWriter and others.
Part 3: (extra credit) The Multi-Torrentor. 
Make the server multi-client capable. Simultaneously, more than one client can request for 
files from the server. Each requesting for a file and the desired number of the chunks.
As in the previous case (Part 2), each client should receive every chunk on a separate connection.

Submission guidelines:
Sign and attach the self-work form. Form is here.
The submission directory should have following structure,
   
     rollno-lab8/
                |_ part1
		  |_ readme        (usage commands to execute client and server)
		  |_ outputs       (sample runs, show at least three runs and corresponding outputs)
		|_ part2
		  |_ readme        (usage commands to execute client and server)
		  |_ outputs       (sample runs, show at least three runs and corresponding outputs)
		|_ part3
		  |_ readme        (usage commands to execute client and server)
		  |_ outputs       (sample runs, show at least three runs and corresponding outputs)

Executing each of the task scripts should generate the associated/correct output. 
Required data files, if any, should in the correct directories or specified via path names as part of command-line arguments. 
If the above commands fail to generate your answers, submission will be treated incomplete.
Create a tar.gz file of your submission. The archive should contain the main directory and all sub-directories. 
Name the tar archive yourrollno-lab7.tar.gz. 
Read up the man page for tar.
Upload the tar.gz file on the moodle site for the course.
submission deadlines: 
      very early deadline: 23/3/12, 4.55 p.m. (max marks: 24) 
      eary deadline: 24/3/12, 4.55 p.m. (max marks: 22)
      absolute deadline: 25/3/12, 4.55 p.m. (max marks: 20) 

